The church at Alcmar was the first among all, which was compelled to institute a separation of this kind. For Adelphus Venator, the pastor of that church, having been suspended from the office of teaching, as well for his too impure life, as for his most impure doctrine, by the churches of North Holland, despising the censures of the churches, nevertheless persisted in the office of teaching.
